The use of the "flipped classroom", a hybrid course design in which some of the traditional lecture material is delivered to students using asynchronous online learning technologies, has seen rapid growth over the past decade. However, at the time this project was initiated the use of flipped classrooms in university-level introductory chemistry courses was not as common compared to other STEM disciplines. To make flipped classrooms more readily available in introductory gateway chemistry courses the NIMBLe Chemistry project team created and implemented a series of flipped modules for the year-long general chemistry and organic chemistry sequences.  Notable achievements include:

1) over 15 flipped classroom modules were created for both the general chemistry and organic chemistry year-long course sequences;

2) a quasi-experimental study revealed a flipped classroom treatment led to significant improvements in course grade compared to a traditional lecture control;

3) a longitudinal study indicated students who participated in a year-long flipped classroom treatment in general chemistry performed better in the first-quarter organic chemistry course than students who experienced traditional classroom environments;

4) experiments utilizing randomized controlled trials found that flipped classroom treatments yield greater learning gains than traditional lecture treatments, and the online learning component resulted in greater learning gains than in-person collaborative group learning within the flipped classroom treatment;

5) the project PIs made arrangements to publish the general chemistry and organic chemistry flipped classroom modules at the IonicViper (Virtual Inorganic Pedagogical Electronic Resource) and OrganicERS (Organic Educational Resources) online faculty resource sites, respectively; and

6) the project PIs will publicize and disseminate the flipped classroom modules through the new ABLE Chemistry website (Active and Blended Learning Chemistry; www.ablechemistry.org).

This project has not only carried out new educational research that strongly suggests the flipped classroom structure has greater impact on student outcomes than traditional lecture environments, it has also created a mechanism by which these new classroom materials can be freely accessed and readily adopted by chemistry instructors who teach a wide variety of class sizes. Because general chemistry and organic chemistry are gateway courses required by many science and engineering majors, this project should ultimately help improve the broader success and retention of students who wish to pursue careers in STEM fields.



